          <h3>7. grantr said...</h3>
          <div class="body"><p>My favorite vim command is definitely :s. Nothing beats vim for easy replace:</p>


	<p>:%s/typo/correction/g</p>


	<p>and you can use &#38; to repeat the last substitution.</p>


	<p>Other highlights:</p>


	<p>Ctrl-] to jump to a tag, and Ctrl-T to jump back.  Try the rails.vim :Rtags command for dead simple taglists!</p>


	<p>do and dp for getting and putting changes in diff mode.  Who needs a fancy merge tool?</p>


	<p>surround.vim.  Awesome stuff:
ysiwttag&gt; : wrap the current word with &lt;tag>&lt;/tag>
cs&#8217;&#8221; : change surrounding &#8217; to &#8221; 
http://www.vim.org/scripts/script.php?script_id=1697</p>


	<p>rails.vim.  Priceless!  The smart gf alone is worth it.
http://rails.vim.tpope.net/</p>


allml.vim.  Great for editing rhtml. And if you have surround.vim, it adds the rhtml tags as surround types!
&lt;insert>Ctrl-= : wrap cursor in &lt;%=  %&gt;
&lt;insert>Ctrl&#8212;: wrap cursor in &lt;%  -%&gt;
http://www.vim.org/scripts/script.php?script_id=1896

	<p>Basically anything Tim Pope has ever done.  He&#8217;s making all other editors obsolete!</p></div>
