          <h3>39. Daniel said...</h3>
          <div class="body"><p>Just a simple one: the &#8216;f&#8217; and &#8217;;&#8217; keys.  If you&#8217;re editing a long line, use f&lt;char> to jump to a character and repeat with &#8217;;&#8217;.  This goes back to vi.  You can combine with c and d etc  &#8216;F&#8217; is reverse.</p>


	<p>I wrote a shell script one time which grepped all my rails files for some name or searched their file names, then created a bunch of sym links in a tmp directory which I then opened in vim.  You can then open each file by using &#8216;o&#8217; which splits the window into the original sym link list and the file name.
But I&#8217;ve been using netbeans and its jvi plugin at the moment.</p>


	<p>Occasionally also use in-built tabbing of vim (as opposed to split or vsplit): &#8221;:tabnew .&#8221;  will open a tab of the current directory etc</p>


	<p>If you&#8217;re in a directory in vim, use &#8217;-&#8217; to go up to the parent dir; &#8216;o&#8217; to open a subdir or file in split window, or just plain &lt;return>.</p></div>
        </div>
        
