          <a name="comment-5080"></a> 

          <h3>86. Jamis said...</h3>
          <div class="body"><p>re #84, most likely you installed a different ruby (via macports, etc.), while macvim tries to use the ruby that ships with <span class="caps">OS X</span>.</p>


	<p>Simple solution: take fuzzy_file_finder.rb and put it in ~/.vim/ruby (you&#8217;ll probably have to create the directory).</p>


	<p>Harder solution: find the ruby executable that ships with <span class="caps">OS X</span>, and the corresponding &#8216;gem&#8217; script, and use that to install the fuzzy_file_finder gem.</p></div>
        </div>
        
