          <h3>111. Cristi Balan said...</h3>
          <div class="body"><p>My vim tip:</p>


	<p>Searching with / takes an offset. The offset allows to move the cursor after a match is made. This is very handy when combined with .</p>


	<p>Given this string: &#8220;blah blah blah&#8221;.</p>


	<p>Let&#8217;s say we want to replace the first and third occurence of ah, with AH.</p>


	<p>/bl/b+2 # =&gt; searches for bl and moves the cursor on top of a
cwAH&lt;esc> # =&gt; changes the ah to AH
n # =&gt; go to second match
n # =&gt; go to third match
. # =&gt; change third match</p>


	<p>:h /</p></div>
        </div>
        
        <div id="comment-5118" class="comment">
